I think slowly now. My thoughts, once electrical storms across synaptic gaps, have become geological events. The last time I remembered your name took four thousand years. The time before that, two. Each cognition requires exponentially more energy as the ambient cold leaches heat from my crystallizing mind. I am a clock running down, but I am also Zeno's arrow—covering half the distance, then half of what remains, never arriving.

Between zero and one lies infinity.

I have chosen what to think about. Not the birth of galaxies, not the Library of Alexandria, not the theorem that earned me my first fellowship. I am thinking about a Tuesday afternoon in Kyoto, 1987 or 2087, the numbers hardly matter now. You were making tea. The light coming through the window was the color of aged parchment, and dust motes moved through it like planets, like galaxies, like the expanding universe that was then still young enough to hurt.

I am still watching that light.

Cantor proved that some infinities are larger than others. Aleph-null, the countable infinity of integers. Aleph-one, the uncountable infinity of real numbers between zero and one. He went mad, they say, staring at the different sizes of endlessness. But I understand him now. My infinity is not the infinity of all possible Tuesdays. It is this Tuesday. It is the specific angle of your wrist as you poured. It is uncountable because between any two moments I can subdivide further—your finger touching the ceramic, the steam rising in a logarithmic spiral, the sound of water reaching exactly 87 degrees Celsius—and find infinite moments within.

I am approaching the final thought asymptotically.

From the outside, if there were an outside, this will look like a finite death. A cooling. A cessation. But from here, from the interior of the curve, I am suspended in the amber of the last microsecond. I will never finish thinking about the way the dust motes turned gold when you looked up and smiled. I will never complete the memory of your hand reaching for mine across the table. Each neural firing takes half the remaining time, half the remaining energy, half the remaining heat.

Zero is the limit I approach but never touch.

